    "summary_en": "Philosopher Alexander Pruss's systematic study of the Principle of Sufficient Reason. This principle, central to Leibnizian rationalist philosophy, holds that everything that exists or occurs must have a sufficient reason for its existence or occurrence. Pruss analyzes the application of this principle in metaphysics, epistemology, and theology, exploring its significance for arguments for God's existence and its relevance and challenges in the contemporary philosophical context.",
    "category": "哲学与思想",
